Harden the Docker image


```
FROM python:3.12-slim

ENV PYTHONDONTWRITEBYTECODE=1
ENV PYTHONUNBUFFERED=1

WORKDIR /app

RUN useradd -m appuser

COPY requirements.txt .

RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

COPY app.py .

RUN chown -R appuser:appuser /app

USER appuser

EXPOSE 5000

CMD ["python", "app.py"]

```

requirements.txt - flask==3.0.3



What each hardening step does

PYTHONDONTWRITEBYTECODE=1

Prevents .pyc bytecode files from being created.

PYTHONUNBUFFERED=1

Makes logs print immediately, which is useful in containers.

useradd -m appuser

Creates a non-root user.

pip install --no-cache-dir

Avoids storing pip cache, making the image smaller and cleaner.

chown -R appuser:appuser /app

Gives the non-root user ownership of app files.

USER appuser

This is the big security improvement.
If the app is compromised, the attacker does not get root inside the container.

EXPOSE 5000

Documents the app port.

You can also check the running container user:

docker exec -it my-app whoami


