###Core Kubernetes concepts (simple)


Pod
Smallest unit → runs container

👉 Like docker run



Deployment
Manages pods (scaling, updates)

👉 Like:

docker-compose service




Service
Exposes app (network access)

👉 Like:

port mapping in Docker



Create your first Kubernetes app
first flask app

deployment.yaml

```
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: my-app
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: my-app
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: my-app
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: my-app
        image: my-app:latest
        ports:
        - containerPort: 5000

```


service.yaml


```
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: my-app-service
spec:
  type: NodePort
  selector:
    app: my-app
  ports:
    - port: 5000
      targetPort: 5000
      nodePort: 30007

```

Apply it 

kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
kubectl apply -f service.yaml

check pods - kubectl get pods

Access app - minikube service my-app-service





⚠️ IMPORTANT (image issue)

Kubernetes cannot see your local Docker image by default.

Fix:

eval $(minikube docker-env)
docker build -t my-app:latest .

Then apply again.




###integrate Jenkins with Kubernetes deployment

For Jenkins, the easiest official-supported way to use kubectl in pipelines is the Kubernetes CLI plugin, which provides kubeconfig setup for pipeline steps. Jenkins pipeline credentials support secret text and secret files, which fits kubeconfig-based auth well

Then add a Kubernetes credential, ideally a kubeconfig file credential for your Minikube cluster. The plugin is specifically meant to let pipeline jobs run kubectl against a cluster.

Export your Minikube kubeconfig

On your Ubuntu VM, your kubeconfig is usually here:

~/.kube/config

Use a real image reference

Kubernetes generally expects an image it can access, which usually means pushing to a registry first, then referencing that image in your Deployment. Container images are typically built and pushed to a registry before being used in Pods.

So your Deployment should eventually use something like:

image: yourdockerhubusername/my-app:latest




Use a real image reference

Kubernetes generally expects an image it can access, which usually means pushing to a registry first, then referencing that image in your Deployment. Container images are typically built and pushed to a registry before being used in Pods.

So your Deployment should eventually use something like:

image: yourdockerhubusername/my-app:latest

jenkins file

```

pipeline {
    agent any

    environment {
        IMAGE_NAME = "yourdockerhubusername/my-app"
        IMAGE_TAG  = "jenkins-${BUILD_NUMBER}"
        ZAP_NET    = "zapnet"
        APP_NAME   = "juice-shop"
    }

    stages {
        stage('Checkout') {
            steps {
                checkout scm
            }
        }

        stage('Build Docker Image') {
            steps {
                sh '''
                docker build -t ${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG} .
                '''
            }
        }

        stage('Run Trivy Gate') {
            steps {
                sh '''
                docker run --rm \
                  -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock \
                  -v $WORKSPACE:/work \
                  aquasec/trivy:0.69.3 image \
                  --severity HIGH,CRITICAL \
                  --ignore-unfixed \
                  --exit-code 1 \
                  --format json \
                  --output /work/trivy-report.json \
                  ${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}
                '''
            }
        }

        stage('Push Image') {
            steps {
                withCredentials([usernamePassword(credentialsId: 'dockerhub-creds', usernameVariable: 'DOCKER_USER', passwordVariable: 'DOCKER_PASS')]) {
                    sh '''
                    echo "$DOCKER_PASS" | docker login -u "$DOCKER_USER" --password-stdin
                    docker push ${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}
                    '''
                }
            }
        }

        stage('Deploy to Kubernetes') {
            steps {
                withKubeConfig([credentialsId: 'minikube-kubeconfig']) {
                    sh '''
                    kubectl get nodes
                    kubectl set image deployment/my-app my-app=${IMAGE_NAME}:${IMAGE_TAG}
                    kubectl rollout status deployment/my-app
                    '''
                }
            }
        }
    }

    post {
        always {
            archiveArtifacts artifacts: 'trivy-report.json', allowEmptyArchive: true, fingerprint: true
        }
    }
}
```

This uses Jenkins credentials for Docker Hub login and withKubeConfig(...) for Kubernetes auth, which is exactly what the Kubernetes CLI plugin is for. The deployment update uses the official kubectl set image flow and waits for rollout completion.

What you must prepare before running that pipeline

Your Kubernetes Deployment must already exist once, with container name my-app. After that, Jenkins can keep updating just the image with kubectl set image. Deployments are the Kubernetes object meant to manage Pods and rollout updates.

Your next actions

Create these Jenkins credentials:

dockerhub-creds → username/password for Docker Hub
minikube-kubeconfig → secret file containing ~/.kube/config

Then update your image name in the Jenkinsfile to your Docker Hub repo name, push the Jenkinsfile, and run the build.

After that, the pipeline becomes:

GitHub → Jenkins → Build → Trivy → Push image → kubectl deploy

That is your first real Jenkins-to-Kubernetes CD flow.




